1474	sea_surface_wind_wave_mean_period_from_variance_spectral_density_first_frequency_moment	\N	s	The wind wave directional spectrum can be written as a  five dimensional function S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction.  S can be integrated over direction to give S1= integral(S dtheta) .  Frequency moments, M(n) of S1 can then be calculated as follows: M(n) = integral(S1 f^n df), where f^n is f to the power of n.  The first wave period, T(m1) is calculated as the ratio M(0)/M(1).	\N
